# Lesson 7: Digital Inputs
## 7.1 Overview

In this lesson, you are going to learn how to use a push button as a digital
input to turn an LED on and off.

## 7.2 Components required
* Development board
* Breadboard 830p
* 2 x push buttons
* 1 x LED
* 1 x 150 Ω resistor
* 7 x male-to-male jumper wires
* Micro USB – Type A USB cable

## 7.3 Components introduction
### Momentary push button switch

This type of button is very common in prototyping as it is breadboard
friendly, cheap and reliable. The way it works is pretty basic: there are 2 lines: A-C
and B-D, which are always connected. When the button is pressed, these two lines AC
and B-D, are connected together, which means that the current will flow from A to
D and from B to C.

![digital_input.png](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## 7.5 Code
The code is very simple. First, we have to declare the pins used by the buttons
and the LED. We will connect the “On” button to D1(GPIO 4) and the “Off” button to D2(GPIO 5). 
The LED will be connected to D7(GPIO 13).

#Digital input LED

from machine import Pin
import time

#set the pin for LED
led = Pin(13, Pin.OUT)

Next step is to set the pins for the
buttons as INPUT_PULLUP and the pin for the LED as OUTPUT.

#create the digital input pin with an internal pull-up resistor
#Pin.IN means the pin will be set as an input that can read high or low levels
#Pin.PULL_UP to enable an internal pull-up resistor on the pin
button_on = Pin(5, Pin.IN, Pin.PULL_UP)
button_off = Pin(4, Pin.IN, Pin.PULL_UP)

In loop we will wait for the buttons to be pressed, and if the On
button was pushed, then the LED will turn On, and if the Off button was pushed,
then the LED will be turned Off. In order to check the state of a button (if it is pressed
or not), you have to use the instruction value(). If the value returned by
this instruction is 0, it means that the button is pressed. Contrary, if the
value is 1, it means that the button is not pressed.

while True:
    # 0 => pressed
    # 1 => release
    
    #check if the button off is pressed
    if button_on.value() and not button_off.value():
        #turn off the LED
        led.off()
        
    #check if the button on is pressed
    elif button_off.value() and not button_on.value():
        #turn on the LED
        led.on()
        
    #wait for 0.1s (100 ms)
    time.sleep(0.01)

Next step is to gently connect the development board to the computer via the
included micro USB cable. There is only one way to plug it in, do not use force to
insert the cable.

To compile the code you should follow the instructions for the board *Adafruit CLUE* from this link:
https://youtu.be/F_4GXU8kKfk?t=585

**Congratulations**, you have completed the tutorial!
